Analysis of mean preference scores demonstrated a consistent aggregate preference by control group participants to allocate scarce health system resources to children across all trial scenarios (Fig. 3
; Table 1
). The strongest control group preference for children was observed in the cancer therapy (-1.77, 95 % CI -2.06 to -1.48, p < 0.0001) and eating disorders treatment (-2.01, 95 % CI -2.30 to -1.71, p < 0.0001) scenarios, in which the theoretical QALY gains were largest.
